                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Now we're talking!
<br />

<br />
Actually, though, I don't think a lawsuit would be successful.  It is true that generally, class action lawsuits are a procedural device designed for collective action problems like the one that, perhaps, the Enchanter community faces.  When the situation is one consumer with minimal damages vs. a big company, the big company has little incentive to do anything in the face of that one consumer's complaint.  When the situation is a class of millions of consumers (and millions of times an individual consumer's damages), then the big company has to do something about it.
<br />

<br />
In order to get a class action certified by a court, however, you've got to jump through some hoops.  The idea is that one person, or a few people, the class representative(s), can basically prosecute a claim against the defendant that is representative of similar claims that many other people possess.  In order to get a class action lawsuit certified, you've got to show <span style="font-weight: bold">numerosity</span>--that the propsed class of plaintiffs is so large that joining the members as seperate plaintiffs in the class would be impractical, <span style="font-weight: bold">commonality</span>--that there are questions of law or fact that are common to the class, <span style="font-weight: bold">typicality</span>--the claims or defenses of the representative parties are typical of the claims or defenses of the class, and <span style="font-weight: bold">adequacy</span>--the representative parties will fairly and adequately protect the interests of the class.
<br />

<br />
Here, I think a putative class action might very well meet those requirements.  The problem wouldn't be certification of the class, it would be merits of the suit itself.
<br />

<br />
Incidentally, the costs of the lawsuit for the plaintiff would be minimal or non-existant.  Genreally class action lawsuits are financed by the lawyers who file them, who will collect a contingent fee upon a successful verdict or settlement.  The lawyers take the risk that the suit will tank (and the money they've spent to prosecute the suit will according be wasted), so they get a cut of the money at the end if the suit is successful.  (Also, in some circumstances the lawyers have a right to fees from the defendant if they are succesful).  However, I think filing a class action lawsuit against sony on these grounds would fail, so no lawyer working on a contingent fee would take the case.  I'm sure that if you had the money to pay a lawyer by the hour to do it, though, you could find one who would take it.
<br />

<br />
Going to Nokei's point: actually, when a seller makes a specific promise about what a product will do, that' called a specific warranty.  An implied warranty of merchantibility comes with just about every sold item, whether the seller disclaims it or not.  The implied warranty means that ever product is presumed to be, well, sellable.  If it isn't, at the time you bought it, then the seller owes you difference between what you thought you were getting and what you got.  That usually translates into a refund, especially with software.
<br />

<br />
Anyway, I don't think Sony is legally liable for anything.  I think we'd have a tough time arguing that reduced pet DPS in OoW makes the expansion worthless, and that every enchanter who bought it deserves a refund.  Some enchanters probably disagree, and because it is a very murky, subjective, and specialized question, the chance that any court would feel like getting involved is about zero.   Also, I imagine the EULA has specific limitations of liability that would predetermine a negative outcome for such a suit.  
<br />

<br />
But hey, if we could get class certification, that would be fun!  Still, I agree that the proper remedy is to make a big public stink and stop giving Sony money. 
<br />

<br />
EDIT: typos!</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=646635" target="_blank" class="postlink">Saediien Iluvatri</a>
<br />
Coercer/The Rathe, account due to expire 11/10/04</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
