                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I'm sorry, but suing over a video game? If *that* doesn't get laughed out of court, I don't know what will.
<br />

<br />
Really, what's your defense going to be? "Judge, SoE promised enchanters during a video game summit that they would listen to their concerns and not nerf them. WELL WE WERE NERFED!"
<br />

<br />
Says the judge - "You're kidding me."
<br />

<br />
Meanwhile, the next people in court who, say, got swindled out of $5,000,000 by a crooked accountant and are waiting for their day in court, must be wondering just how seriously some people take a video game.
<br />

<br />
Honestly, if you were ripped off and want to sue Sony, the most you'll get is $30 back for the price of the expansion.
<br />

<br />
If you're that pissed off, cancel your account and demand your money back.
<br />

<br />
If, on the other hand, you're STILL paying for this game month in and month out, and expect to SUE the company for ... I don't know ... letting you pay to play their game? I'm just flabbergasted by the reasoning behind that.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />It's easy to use - if you're one of the 2% of the population who thinks logically and can read an instruction manual. The other 98% of the population would find it very hard or impossible to use.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
